      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The strongest philosophical arguments for this stance come from the libertarian tradition, particularly John Stuart Mill's \"On Liberty\" (1859), which argues that government regulation of speech is a form of paternalism that infringes upon an individual's right to express themselves freely. The concept of \"harm principle\" also supports this view, as it asserts that government intervention in speech should only occur when it prevents harm to others. Additionally, the First Amendment's protection of free speech in the US Constitution serves as a foundational principle for this argument.",
